Chapter 5 Results 5.1 Overview for New York State 5.1.1 The overall trend of the average count per hour per street from 2018 to 2020 We first analysed the overall trend of the traffic data in the New York state to get an overview. In general, we can see the streets in the New York State is busy in the first three months in each year. The general trend and level are very similar between 2018 and 2019, but the counts for the first half of the year of 2020 is much lower than other years, which suggested us that there may be some effects from the COVID-19. We have also noticed that there is no data for the January and February for 2020, this may due to the COVID-19 or other errors in the dataset, but there is no official explanation for them. 5.1.2 The comparison between rural and urban areas for their trend of the average count 5.1.3 The distribution of vehicle count among different regions in New York State from 2018 to 2020 From the plots above, streets in New York City are always the busiest among regions in New York State from 2018 to 2020. 5.1.4 The distribution of vehicle count among different weekdays in New York State from 2018 to 2020 From the plot above, streets in New York States are busiest on Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday, and least busy on Friday from 2018 to 2020. 5.1.5 The busiest streets in New York State from 2018 to 2020 From the plots above, we can see there are more busy streets from New York City(NYC) from 2018 to 2020, and it turns out that the 15 busiest streets are all from NYC on 2020. This suggest us that there may be something different between NYC and other counties, and we should take a closer look to NYC. 5.2 Closer Look at the New York City
